<subSubSection pageId="72" pageNumber="71" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="72.[192,1440,835,955]" pageId="72" pageNumber="71">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,324,835,859]" pageId="72" pageNumber="71">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species has male genitalia closely similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gordon and Hanley" authorityYear="2017" box="[1016,1099,836,859]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Prodilis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cora">
<emphasis box="[1016,1034,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="71">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1047,1099,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="71">cora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gordon and Hanley" authorityYear="2017" box="[1156,1235,835,859]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Prodilis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="faye">
<emphasis box="[1156,1174,836,859]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="71">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1187,1235,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="71">faye</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is separated from those taxa by dorsal color pattern and male head comparatively narrow and distinctly patterned. Prosternal structure is most similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gordon and Hanley" authorityYear="2017" box="[731,812,900,923]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Prodilis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="72" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cora">
<emphasis box="[731,749,900,923]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="71">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[761,812,900,923]" italics="true" pageId="72" pageNumber="71">cora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the lateral carina do not extend to the prosternal base.
</paragraph>
